<Author>Kezsin
<Content>An Oasis Getaway We arrived on a Saturday afternoon - almost over an hour's drive from the Airport @ Denpasar.The Property has a narrow entrance, identified by the Four Seasons Sign along a narrow road. Infact, all roads in Bali are narrow. Vehicles are thoroughly checked prior to entry - which was a definite plus point as we doubt whether we were in any mood for fireworks at this time of the year.Check-in was a breeze. When we sighted the property, it reminded us of our visits to the Datai Villa @ Langkawi - but the Four Seasons were of a class on its own and amidst a Bali-natural setting. We noticed that a lot of care and attention was invested to blend the resort into its lush environment of tropical green and padi fields. Remarkable.We were shown to our room - a Villa really - and was taken by the impressive architecture - an Englishman's creation. Lots of stairs (this wasn't going to score any brownie points), and a lot of water features (now, that will score a brownie point). The canals of water leading us to the Villa was a welcome sight - coupled with the gentle water flows. Relaxing effect it produced.The rooms were a sight to hold. Coming into the open area on top, and walking down the stairs to the bedroom below. Every detail was carefully thought out.The overall experience was exceptional. The staff (we understand was the best of the best) certainly made every effort to make your stay hospitable. There was even a hand-written note from the Manager welcoming us to the Resort. It is also as if every staff was trained to know your name and to address you by your name.We had a complain about the air-conditioner that wasn't working in our Villa, and was straightaway upgraded to a private Chalet with a private pool. We were fascinated with the promptness in attending to any complains. I must also point out that we forgot our Baby's shampoo, and the hotel staff made sure we had all the Babies' supplies (and cot) before we occupied the room. I don't know of many hotels that provide Mamipoko nappies - and it sure was impressive (not that we used any as the size was a little small).There was also a request to check the water-heater as I felt it wasn't working as it should. The request was promptly carried out by the hotel staff - discreetly - and upon completion of the investigation, we were delivered a cocktail of fine chocolates with a personal note of apology. Courtesy seems generously abundant in this Resort that one is ready to overlook any short-comings encountered.The private Chalets (they cost more), was again, a class of its own. Entrance was via a staircase (a spiral-cork screw passage made of crafted stone), that descended below the padi fields facing out into the lush greens beyond.The private pool was so private. That leaves much to the imagination .... to be one with nature.But we missed the Villas, so we requested a transfer back to the Villas the day after. We found the Villas to be more accomodating as it was attached to the main lobby and restaurant. Besides, there was no need to keep waiting for the buggy to take us from the Chalet.One note on the Restaurant : the waiters are friendly and will offer you beverages as if it was all complimentary. But the truth is you'd be charged for every juice poured into your drink whether its refill or a second glass of something else, and coffee/tea don't come free - even if you don't drink it at all. But when you stay at this Resort, its best you forget money has any more value. Its the service you want, and it will be the service you get.We had a superb stay at the Four Seasons, and it was our Baby's first long-distance get-away. 
